snippet.textDisplay:
A H E M
This comment is going to be tedious for some of you.
Be warned.

Hazmat suit is way too hot and baggy, armor is too heavy and makes a lot of sounds.
So just tape yourself.
Souvenir katanas will be pretty much useless due to material of the blade, and after all it is best to stick with some polearms to maintain a safe distance during a fight with zombies, such as war scythe or a halberd, both can be made pretty easily.
Gas masks have a downside of requiring spare filters, which are pretty much heavy. Also, filters are not universal, and most of the civil filters won't help against biological contamination due to the very little size of virus moleculas. Still, maybe they will help.
Also it would be a good idea to have something soft on your boot soles, to make less noise when moving around.
Making survival thingies always remember the importance of the simplicity. Complex designs may be universal, but they take a lot of time and resources to make, and if you're travelling like a post-apocalyptic nomad, you'd like to have more time on preparing your next move. Better make something simple and solid, what can serve well for a certain amount of time and what can be disposed of easily. Complexity will be reasonable only when you'll find a place to settle at.

See ya'll during ZA! And don't eat all brains without me!

snippet.textDisplay: If we're talking realistically, in the event that a serious zombie outbreak type scenario were to come to pass the government would have had it under control since day 1. But if we still want to talk about survival plans, then you're going to want to consider a few things. The moment there are reports on the news of some type of new virus that's turning people into these monsters, consider your location (inner city, country, or suburban type area) and plan accordingly. If you're in the city, people are leaving abandoned cars in the streets. So just packing up and driving away won't be a viable option. Form a safehouse type base, and bunker down. For the other two, you're going to want to stock up on gas for transport and possibly trading. Gasoline has a shelf life of about 3 to 6 months given that it's properly stored in a labeled, tightly sealed plastic container or metal tank. Next, if you're going to form a group, make it a small one. More people just means more mouths to feed (a good size is about 4-5 people, including you). Now, while everyone is going to be killing each other over resources at the grocery stores and gun shops, I'm going to go the local Bass Pro shop or any other hunting and sporting goods store and stock up on gear there instead. I'm going to want to travel lightly, so items I'd personally bring are: a sidearm (a standard 1911 pistol would be preferable, with a thigh holster for easy retrieval) a crossbow with a built-in bolt holder (holds about 3-4 extra bolts on average), a survival bag, a melee weapon of some kind (I'd bring a machete), a sleeping bag, and about 5 days worth of food and water. If possible and you still have room to spare, then bring one weapon you specialize with (for me it would be a shotgun with a few additional boxes of ammo, but not too much. Ammo by itself is heavy. Only use it for serious situations only). Now you might be thinking, "But why would you only take a regular pistol? Wouldn't bigger weapons be better at killing things?" And yes, you would be right. However, you're more likely to find regular 9 mm rounds rather than shotgun shells or assault rifle rounds when looting. And that particular weapon is easier to maintain than a rifle sized gun that takes longer to take apart and clean. Now it's time to think long term, in a world where the majority of the population has turned already basic services such as water, electricity, sanitation, and medicine won't be available. You're 10 times more likely to die from a regular cut without the proper medical supplies. So it's time to hit up your local pharmacy for supplies and extra food (given you have a vehicle readily available). Once you have yourself and your group well situated, then you can start thinking about whether or not to leave your current area and move somewhere away from people, or to find a place to set up as a semi-permanent base. I think about this way too often. But hey, maybe it'll come in handy one day.

snippet.textDisplay:
Here is the EASIEST way to survive an apacolype.

1: have a phone with service with full country cover

2: grab ALOT of water, food is secondary.

3: DO NOT USE A BLUNT WEAPON OR SLASHING WEAPONS. Use a shovel or anything with stabbing capabilities and ONLY STAB. No certainty that the disease can also be transmitted through blood.

4: the ultimate step: escape to somewhere incredibly cold/hot. Anywhere on the equator is a good choice and a desert can work too if you have what you need to last a week.

5. Hold out 1-2 weeks to let the zombies decompose and athrophy so they're unable to move and die.

And thus, you survived?

snippet.textDisplay: Nope... All wrong.  I live in NY, so I make my way to the nearest waterway that will get me to the ocean or go straight to the ocean.  Then go from boat to boat or just one boat collecting fuel along the way. BTW- I already own like a dozen guns and have probably about 30,000 rounds of ammo. (I'm not crazy, I just buy ammo when it's on sale, and I only go shooting like twice a year now since I moved).  Anyway... while making my way down the east coast I will eventually stumble across a large yacht with a tender and everything (probably a lot of them).  Pick one with a massive (full) fuel tank.  Continue heading down south and make my way to the Bahamas.  Clear the island, collect all the fishing\crabbing gear, car batteries, solar chargers, ext ext ext.... Live out my happy life (with no zombies) and deal with the occasional hurricane.  No zombies, no freezing to death, hopefully no crazy people, live on my luxury yacht, with all my solar chargers and power converters.  I would have also been collecting laptops and other electric devices along the way. (I work in IT and have probably 200+ 500GB-2TB hard drives from work). I also have like 8TB of movies and TV shows saved.  I'd back up everything multiple times over.  Spend my life fishing, crabbing, watching movies and stuff at night.  The End!

Continue heading down south and make my way to the Bahamas.  Clear the island, collect all the fishing\crabbing gear, car batteries, solar chargers, ext ext ext.... Live out my happy life (with no zombies) and deal with the occasional hurricane.  No zombies, no freezing to death, hopefully no crazy people, live on my luxury yacht, with all my solar chargers and power converters.  I would have also been collecting laptops and other electric devices along the way. (I work in IT and have probably 200+ 500GB-2TB hard drives from work). I also have like 8TB of movies and TV shows saved.  I'd back up everything multiple times over.  Spend my life fishing, crabbing, watching movies and stuff at night.  The End!
